ilet purposes. Don't fall to In\nclude Cuticura Talcum.\u2014Adv.\nWedding Ring Finger.\nWhatever the fashion may be about\nwedding rings, the Episcopal Book of\nOommon Prayer says: \"The priest,\ntaking the ring, shall deliver It to the\nman to pnt on the fourth finger of the\nwoman's left hand.\"\nIts\ned\nLUCKYSTRIKE\ncigarette. Flavor is\nseated in by\nWATCir\nTHE BIG 4\nStomaoh-Kidneya-Heart-Lbrer\nKeep the vital organs healthy by\nregularly taking the world's stand\nard remedy for kidney, liver,\nand uric add troubles\u2014\nGOLD MEDAL\nTha National Remedy of Holland for\ncenturies end endorsed by Queen Wilhel\nmioa. At all druggists, three sisae.\nled fee S mmmMA H rid w evety bee\nComing Out\nA\nm\na*\nf\n\u00abr\n-a\nWti\n-i'L*\n38\n\ni\nm\u00e0\n\n\u00eb\nS\u00bb'\nmx&a\nCABINET WOULD\nBOOST BUSINESS\nDISCUSS PLANS FOR EXTENDING\nDOMESTIC AND FOREIGN\nCOMMERCE.\nWashington. How to boost Amer\nican business at home and abroad\nwas the principal subject of discus\nsion at a recent meeting of President\nHarding with his cabinet.\nThe president took an optimistic\nview of the present period of business\ndepression. He reported to his offi\ncial advisers the gubstance of the\ntalks he has had in the last few days\nwith the heads of great industries,\nlike James A. Farrell, of the United\nStates Steel Corporation.\nInformation which has come to the\npresident in this way is that the\nlow tide of business depression has\nbeen passed and that conditions are\nbeginning to improve in those indus\ntries, particularly those which have\nbeen hit by the buying slump and\nfall in prices.\nMr. Harding directed the cabinet\ndiscussion to the consideration of def\ninite policies for fostering the expan\nsion of domestic and foreign com\nmerce, which he sums up as the pro\nmotion of national prosperity, one of\nthe highest functions of government.\nThe president indicated that he fa\nvors the abolition of fettering re\nstrictions imposed on industrial and\nagricultural development and a great\ned degree of co-operation between\nthe government and the business ac\ntivities of the country.\nIn the field of foreign commerce\nthe president cited the fact that the\nlack of government co-operation and\noutright restrictions had served to\nplace American business at a disad\nvantage in competing with foreigners\nwhose governmfents are extremely\npaternalistic in the promotion of\nforeign trade. Such foreign paternal\nism takes the form of government\nsubsidies of ship lines and the exten\nsion of banking and marketing facili\nties to exporters.\nWhile not advocating direct subsi\ndies to American ship lines, the\npresident was of the opinion that\nAmerican ships should be relieved of\nthe payment of Panama canal tolls\nand that the government should fur\nnish the same aid to exporters en\nojyed by their foreign competitors.\nSecretary of Commerce Hoover ex\npressed the opinion that one of the\nfirst steps taken should be the amend\nment of the Webb-Pomerene act,\nwhich permits combination of export\ners, so as to enable them to operate\ndistributing agencies abroad. He also\ndescribed his plan for advisory com\nmittees of the principal Industries of\nthe country which will co-operate\nwith the government in developing\nthe production and marketing of the\nsort of goods required by foreign cus\ntomers. He will formulate this plan\nat a meeting with a committee of the\nChamber of Commerce of the United\nStates in the near future.\nCaillaux In Riot.\nGrenoble, France.\u2014Many persons\nwere injured in rioting here ouside a\ntheater where Joseph Caillaux, form\ner premier, was delivering a lecture\nunder auspices of the Socialist muni\ncipality andthe League for the Rights\nof Man. M. Caillaux was freed In\n1920 after having been sentenced to\nseveral years' imprisonment for his\n\"defeatist\" policy during the war.#\nBank Closes Doors.\nBeaver, Pa.\u2014The First National\nBank of Beaver has closed its doors.\nFred Wilson, vice president, said that\nan examination of the bank's books\ndisclosed an irregularity, and the\nbank was closed for an Investigation\nand to'protect interests of the stock\nholders.\nRate Argument End$.\nWashington. Arguments In the\nWisconsin rate case, described by\nsome participating attorneys as the\n\"tnost Important states' rights issue\nbefore the Supreme Court In many\nyears,'' has been closed.\nWill Reduce Wages.\nPhiladelphia. The Pennsylvania\nRailroad announced it will post no\ntices Informing all officers and em\nployes that It proposes to reduce sal\nari\u00e9e and wages, effective April 20.\nBRIAND CONFIDENT\nGERMANS CAN PAY\nSAYS THAT THEY WILL EVENT\nUALLY DISCOVER THEIR\nRESOURCES.\nParis.\u2014The allied reparations com\nmission, in its note to Germany de\nmanding fulfillment of article 235 of\nthe peace treaty, notified the Ger\nman government it must pay one bil\nlion gold marks before March 23, it\nwas announced. The money must be\ndeposited in the Bank of France,\nBank of England or the Federal Re\nserve Bank in the United States, Ger\nmany was told.\nIt must complete the payment of\n20,000,000,000 gold marks by May 1.\nThe commission gave Germany un\ntil April 1 to submit a proposal to\npay the balance of the 20,000,000,000\nmarks otherwise than in cash.\nGermany may submit a plan for a\nforeign loan by April 1 with the pro\nceeds of which shall be payable to\nthe commission. The commission an\nnounced that Germany had virtually\nrefused to pay the balance, asserting\nthe 20,000,000,000 marks had been ful\nly paid.\nPremier Briand, replying to .inter\npellations in the Chamber of Depu\nties regarding the London reparations\nconference, said that if the allies re\nmain firm and united the Germans\nwill discover that they (the Germans)\nhave astonishing resources. Germany\nhad been vanquished, he declared,\nj but, unfortunately, psychologically\nthis was insufficiently apparent to the\nGerman people.\nM. Briand told the Chamber he\nwent to the London conference bound\nto maintain the reparations figures\narrived at in Paris, but ready to make\nconcessions regarding the methods of\npayment\n\"I frankly told our allies there was\na wall against which we were back\ned,\" lie declared.\nCrossing Crash Fatal.\nCuero, Tex. Mrs. D. B. Frils was\ninstantly killed and her husband, D.\nB. Frils was probably fatally injured\nwhen their automobile was struck by\na Southern Pacific train, three miles\neast of Cuero. Their son, Willie, es\ncaped.\nWill Sign Trade Pact.\nLondon.\u2014The Anglo-Russian trade\nagreement will be signed. Negotia\ntions between Leonid Krassin, the\nRussian representative, and the Board\nof Trade have resulted in reframing\nsome of the clauses in a manner ac\nceptable to the British government.\nTo Clean Up St. Louis.\nBt. Louis.\u2014A force of about 30 fed\ni eral prohibition enforcement agents,\nsome from New York and some from\nArkansas,are bene for the purpose, it\nwas announced, of \"'cleaning up\" St\nLouis.\nWill Visit Mexico.\nNew Orleans.\u2014Acting on a formal\nInvitation from President Obregon, 80\nNew Orleans business men have left\nfor Brownsville, Tex., where they\nwill cross Into Mexico for a trade ex\ntension trip of 17 days.\nAmerican Ship Missing.\nj London. The American freight\nI steamer Hewitt, which left Sabine\nJanuary 20 for Boston, bas been post\ned as missing. The steamer which\nhas a normal crew of 54, has a gross\ntonnage of 5,398.\nTo Consider Wage Cut.\nAtlanta, GaJr-The Nashville, Chat\ntanooga and St. Louis railroad has\nannounced that it had requested a\nconference of represen\u00e9ativee of its\nunskilled laborers\u00ab in Nashville to\npropose a wage reduction.\n1 Managua.\nPremier's Slayer Held.\nMadrid.\u2014Anatenoto Pedro Mateo,\nan anarchist, was arrested and, ac\ncording to the police, confessed to\nthe assassination of Premier Dato.\nHe gave the names of alleged accom\nplices. j.\nWithdrawal Not Asked.\nManagua. Nicaragua. The Sen\nate has rejected a motion to request\nthe United States to withdraw the\nAmeifcan troops stationed In\nM rs. nancy sharp, of\nLos Angeles, who says she\nreceived the greatest surprise of\nher life when Tanlac completely\nrestored her health after she had\nalmost lost hope of ever getting\nwell. Suffered twelve years.\n\"After seeing the wonderful results\nmy husband obtained from Tanlac I\nbegan taking the medicine myself, and\nnow we both agree that it is the\ngrandest medicine on earth,\" said Mrs.\nNancy Sharp, a prominent and highly\nesteemed resident of Los Angeles,\nCalif., living at 921 Caniulus street,\nwhose husband is proprietor of the\nMerchants' Express Co.\n\"During the twelve years that 1\nsuffered with indigestion and stomach\ntrouble I tried nearly every medicine\nI heard about, but nothing helped me\nand I lost faith in everything. So.\nmy wonderful restoration to health\nhas been the greatest surprise of my\nlife.\n\"I began to feel an improvement on\nfinishing my second bottle of Tanlac,\nand now after taking six bottles I am\nlike a new woman. I have a splendid\nappetite, eat three hearty meals a day,\nenjoy them thoroughly and am never\ntroubled in the least with indigestion\nor any other disagreeable after ef\nfects.\n\"Before taking Tanlac most every\nthing I ate caused my stomach to\nrebel and I would suffer for hours\nafterwards. I was so dreadfully\nnervous that many nights I never\nclosed my eyes in sleep, but now l\nam not the least nervous, and I eep\nlike a child. My strength has been\nwonderfully increased, and I have\nmuch more energy.\n\"I just wish it was so everybody\ntroubled like I was knew about this\nwonderful medicine.\"\nTanlac is sold by leading druggists\neverywhere.\u2014Adv.\nHis Choice.\n\"I want a ouija board.\"\n\"What kind?\"\n\"Give me one that can spell.\"\nSWAMP-ROOT FOR\nKIDNEY AILMENTS\nThere is only one medicine that really\n\u2022tends out pre-eminent as a medicine for\n,-urable ailments of the kidneys, liver and\nDiadder.\nDr. Kilmer's Swamp-Ro